    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Could it be a nitrogen deficiency though? I read somewhere that nitrogen moves from old leaves to new ones, which might be why the bottom ones are yellowing first. If it is nitrogen, how do I fix the soil? I might need to adjust the pH too.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, nitrogen deficiency is a plausible explanation, especially if the leaves are old and have already utilized most of the available nitrogen. Tomatoes do have a natural process called \"nitrogen remobilization,\" where older leaves release nitrogen to support new growth. However, if the nitrogen levels are low, it can cause the lower leaves to yellow and drop off. To address the issue, you can add a balanced fertilizer to the soil, such as a 10-10-10 NPK (nitrogen-phosphorus-potassium) formula. As for pH, tomatoes typically prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH between 6.0 and 6.8, so it's unlikely that the pH is the main issue.",
      "source": "target",
